      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym tones (dumbbell metallic, bench or floor neutral/dark, natural/soft lighting), with soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight back/arm muscles and form\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (small dumbbell clink, subtle breath), no voice-over (optional soft breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with a flat bench (or stable support) and dumbbell. Clean, uncluttered background; floor stable.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — enough to capture full upper-body, bench (or support), dumbbell, and the pulling motion path.\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, wearing workout clothes (t-shirt/tank + shorts/leggings), one knee + hand resting on bench (or free-hand if using alternative support), other foot on ground, back roughly parallel to bench/floor, ready to row.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — place one knee and same-side hand on bench; other foot planted firmly on floor; opposite hand grips dumbbell with neutral grip; spine neutral / flat, core braced, shoulder blades relaxed but ready.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — engage core and glutes, retract shoulder blades slightly to stabilize upper back; lifter prepares to pull.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull — exhale, drive elbow upward and back toward hip/torso, pulling dumbbell in controlled arc close to side of body. Emphasize moving elbow rather than just curling with arm.\n* 4 s–5 s: Top / contraction — dumbbell at highest point (near hip / side of chest), pause ~0.2–0.5 s; squeeze upper-back (lats/rhomboids), keep torso stable, shoulder blades retracted/stable.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / return — inhale, slowly lower dumbbell back to full extension (arm near floor), maintaining control and neutral spine.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish / ready for next rep — dumbbell down, upper-body stable, bench support clear; brief hold (~0.3 s), then optional fade out or next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Back — especially the Latissimus dorsi (lats), plus mid-back muscles like Rhomboids and Trapezius.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Rear shoulders (posterior deltoids), biceps/forearms (as elbow flexors), core/stabilizer muscles (to keep torso rigid and avoid swing), also lower-back and hips to some extent.\nBenefits & Why It’s Valuable\n* Unilateral training — helps address left-right strength or muscle imbalances since each side works independently.\n* Good back thickness and “V-shape” development — because it hits lats, rhomboids, traps, creating width and depth.\n* Core and stability engagement — supporting arm/leg + controlled torso helps improve core stability, posture, and lower-back health.\n* Flexibility & control over load — easy to scale up or down based on available dumbbell, and good for both strength and hypertrophy.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Keep back flat and spine neutral — avoid rounding or arching. Use hip hinge / bench support to stabilize.\n* Lead with the elbow, not the hand — this ensures back muscles (lats, rhomboids) drive the movement instead of biceps.\n* Avoid torso rotation or swing — maintain stability, and don’t twist body during pull to reduce lower-back stress.\n* Choose a weight you can control through full range of motion — high reps with controlled form better than heavy loads with bad form.",
