      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real gym-style lighting (or clean home-gym lighting), neutral tones (machine grey/black, gym bench/chair, subject in workout clothes), soft key light + ambient fill to highlight subject, bar and back muscles\n* Sound: Soft ambient: slight cable/weight stack clink, soft seat/foot shuffle, subtle breath — no voice-over (or optional gentle cue), focusing on atmosphere and controlled movement\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable/pulldown machine in gym (or home-gym with appropriate pulley setup), seat adjusted, thigh pad snug to secure your legs, feet flat on floor. Background simple or softly blurred so focus stays on lifter + bar + back.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle or slightly front/side — capturing full upper-body, seat, bar path — so you can clearly see posture, grip, bar lowering path and back contraction.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing gym clothes (tank or fitted tee + shorts/training pants), seated with thighs under pad, feet grounded, torso upright, ready to pull.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject grips bar with hands slightly wider than shoulder-width (overhand / pronated grip), arms fully extended overhead; chest up, back straight, scapula relaxed (shoulders down & back), thighs secured under pad; core & glutes engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace & engage — retract scapula (pull shoulder blades down & back), create tension; prepare to pull — posture strong, torso stable.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Concentric phase — exhale, drive elbows down & back (not just pull with arms), pull bar toward upper chest/ collarbone (or sternum) — focus on lat/back contraction, not on swinging body or using momentum.\n* 4 s–5 s: Squeeze / Hold — bar at bottom position, elbows down/back, shoulder blades squeezed together, lats engaged, chest up; hold ~0.2–0.5 s to emphasize contraction and muscle activation.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return / Eccentric phase — inhale, slowly raise bar back to overhead (arms fully extended), with control (don’t let weight slam, don’t let shoulders shrug). Maintain posture, keep scapula stable, core engaged.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / Ready — arms extended overhead, back upright, core & posture still stable; prepare for next rep or finish clip — optional slight pause before fade.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (“lats”) — main target for pulldown movement.\n* Secondary/Supporting: Middle & upper back (rhomboids, trapezius), rear shoulders (posterior deltoids), biceps & forearms (for elbow flexion/stabilization), plus core & grip for stability.\nBenefits / Why Use Lat Pulldown\n* Develop a wider, stronger back — lat width helps with “V-taper” and posture.\n* Good isolation & controlled strength work — because you’re seated and stabilized, it’s easier to maintain strict form than with some body-weight pulls or free-weight rows.\n* Adjustable resistance — good for trainees at any level (beginner → advanced), easier to manage progression without lifting full body-weight (as in pull-ups).\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Keep back straight and chest up — avoid excessive leaning or arching of spine while pulling.\n* Pull with elbows, not hands — lead movement by driving elbows down/back to better engage lats and minimize biceps dominance.\n* Avoid using momentum or swinging — control both descent and return; maintain stable torso & core throughout.\n* Use proper seat/pad setup — knees secured under thigh-pad, feet flat, to prevent body lift and ensure isolation of back muscles.\n* Choose manageable weight — ensure you can control full range of motion without sacrificing form (especially control on eccentric/return phase).",
