      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real gym lighting or neutral gym-style tone (cable machine metallic parts, darker/matte gym floor or background, warm/neutral skin tones); add a soft key light + gentle ambient to highlight your back, arms, and cable path\n* Sound: Soft ambient — faint cable/weight stack movement, subtle breath, perhaps slight foot shuffle when stepping back; no voice-over (or optional soft cue like “exhale/pull”)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable-pulley machine (high pulley) in a gym or home-gym — top‐pulley set, cable attachment (straight bar or rope) ready; space in front of machine so subject can stand and step back with room. Background minimal or slightly blurred to keep focus on subject + movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle from front-slightly-side (or side-slightly low) — captures full upper body, bar/ring, cable tower, and range of motion from overhead start to hip/side-thigh finish.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing gym clothes (tank or fitted tee + shorts/training pants), standing with feet about shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, ready to perform the pulldown.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — stand facing cable machine; grab the bar/attachment with overhand (pronated) grip about shoulder-width apart; arms extended upward (hands overhead), cable taut; slight hinge at hips (torso angled ~20–30° forward), chest up, core & glutes engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — tighten core, retract and depress shoulder blades (shoulders back & down), maintain straight/near-straight arms (slight elbow micro-bend for safety), body stable; prepare to pull.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Concentric phase — exhale, contract lats and pull the bar down in a controlled downward arc such that arms travel toward hips/upper thighs, keeping arms straight; imagine “pulling the bar to your sides” or “driving elbows down and back.”\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom / Contraction hold — bar near or just above thighs; shoulder blades retracted; feel maximal lat contraction, slight squeeze; hold briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) to emphasize muscle engagement.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return / Eccentric phase — inhale, allow the cable to slowly raise arms back overhead in controlled arc, resisting momentum; maintain slight bend in elbows, keep torso upright (or same hinge), control throughout.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish / Reset pose — arms overhead/extended, cable taut, body stable, chest up, ready for next rep or fade to black.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — main driver of shoulder-extension & arm-pull motion.\n* Secondary: Teres major, rear deltoids (posterior deltoids), long head of Triceps brachii (as stabilizer since elbows remain relatively straight), and stabilizer muscles: core (abs/obliques), lower back, and shoulder-girdle stabilizers.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Great lat isolation — because arms stay straight, you minimize biceps/triceps involvement and fully load the lats through a long range of motion (full stretch overhead → full contraction at hips).\n* Helps improve mind-muscle connection with lats — useful for lifters who struggle to “feel” their back doing the work in rows or pulldowns.\n* Can serve as back warm-up / activation movement before heavy pulling or deadlifts, improving shoulder & lat control, posture, and reducing risk of lower-back stress.\n* Useful as finisher or accessory movement — helps shape back width, improves shoulder health, works posterior chain synergistically when done with proper form.\nCommon Mistakes to Avoid & Key Technique Tips\n* Don’t bend elbows significantly — keep arms nearly straight throughout. Bending turns it into a triceps or biceps-dominant move (less lat isolation).\n* Avoid using momentum: don’t jerk, swing, or lean back — control both downward pull and upward return. Use moderate/light weight to maintain form.\n* Maintain a slight hip-hinge and stable core — a rigid torso helps isolate lats and prevents stress on lower back or spine.\n* Full range of motion matters — stretch lats at top (arms overhead) and contract fully at bottom (arms by hips) to maximize muscle stimulus.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — main driver of shoulder-extension & arm-pull motion.\n* Secondary: Teres major, rear deltoids (posterior deltoids), long head of Triceps brachii (as stabilizer since elbows remain relatively straight), and stabilizer muscles: core (abs/obliques), lower back, and shoulder-girdle stabilizers.",
