      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional compound-lift clip — about 8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym lighting (metal barbell, plates, gym floor), neutral/dark tones; soft directional key-light + ambient fill to highlight form & muscle tension\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (plates on floor, subtle bar grip noise, controlled breath), no voice-over (or optional subtle breath-cue)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym floor with a barbell on the ground (plates loaded) — floor space cleared, bar centered.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) — to show full body from head to feet, bar, and motion path (floor → standing).\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult Male, athletic build, wearing simple gym clothes (tank/tee + shorts or gym pants), feet under/near bar, preparing lift.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — lifter stands with feet roughly hip- to shoulder-width, barbell close to shins/over mid-foot, toes slightly outward; grip on bar just outside knees, hands even. Shoulders over or slightly in front of bar, spine neutral, chest up.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — engage core and glutes, retract/pack shoulders slightly ( “tight lats” ), take a deep breath, prepare to lift.\n* 2 s–3 s: Initial pull — lift bar by extending hips and knees simultaneously; keep bar close to legs; back stays flat/neutral; push “through feet into ground,” not jerking.\n* 3 s–5 s: Up-phase / Lockout — rise till standing upright: hips full extension, knees locked (or straight), shoulders back, chest up; barbell rests at thigh level. Muscles (glutes, hamstrings, back) under full contraction.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lowering / descent — hinge at hips and bend knees while maintaining flat back, lower bar back to floor under control; keep bar close, avoid rounding spine.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / ready for next rep — bar settled on floor, lifter stable, chest up, core braced; brief pause then repeat or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\nThe deadlift engages a large number of muscle groups; some key ones are:\n* Lower body / hips / posterior chain: Glutes (gluteus maximus), hamstrings, hamstring-complex, and hip muscles — responsible for hip extension and power.\n* Legs (quads & supporting leg muscles): Quadriceps assist, especially during knee extension portion.\n* Back & spine stabilizers: Spinal erectors (lower back), lats, upper- and mid-back muscles (trapezius, rhomboids) — help keep spine neutral and stabilize torso.\n* Core / trunk: Abs, obliques and core stabilizers — for spine stability and transfer of force from lower to upper body.\n* Upper body / grip / forearms: Forearms, grip muscles, and even shoulders (to some extent) — because you hold the bar and control it throughout.\nBenefits / Why Use Deadlift\n* Very efficient full-body strength builder — because of the many muscle groups engaged, it's one of the most effective compound lifts for overall strength & muscle mass.\n* Great for posterior-chain development — helps improve glutes, hamstrings, lower-back strength, posture, and functional strength for everyday movements (lifting, carrying).\n* Core and stability improvement — deadlift demands strong core and spinal control, which can benefit posture and reduce risk of back injuries (when done properly).\n* Enhances overall strength and power — as a foundational lift, good for athletic performance, powerlifting, strength training, or general fitness.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Notes\n* Maintain a neutral spine — not rounded, not over-arched. Spine alignment is crucial to avoid lower-back injuries.\n* Keep the bar close to your body — as you lift, the bar should track close to shins/thighs; this reduces leverage on lower back and improves efficiency.\n* Use hip + knee extension together — don’t treat it like a squat or purely back lift; deadlift is a coordinated hip-hinge move.\n* Start light and focus on form — especially if new. Once technique is solid, load can be progressively increased.\n* Avoid jerky motions or sudden bounce — lift and lower in a smooth, controlled manner, focusing on muscle tension and control, not momentum.",
