      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym or home-gym tones — neutral/dark gym floor or bench, metal barbell/dumbbells (if used), warm/neutral skin tones; soft key-light + gentle ambient fill to highlight back, arms, weight, posture\n* Sound: Soft ambient (weight clinks, floor creak, subtle breath), no voice-over (or optional breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with enough space, and equipment: either a barbell (floor or rack) or a pair of dumbbells + optional bench for support\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing full upper-body and torso from head to knees, including the weight (barbell/dumbbell), back and arm movement, and floor/bench if needed\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing gym-appropriate clothing (t-shirt/tank + shorts/leggings), prepared in bent-over (hip-hinge) or one-arm row posture\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — stand with feet hip- to shoulder-width (or stagger if using bench support), grasp barbell or dumbbell with overhand or neutral grip; hinge at hips, bend knees slightly, torso angled forward (~45–60°), spine neutral, head in neutral alignment, core and glutes engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — retract shoulder blades slightly, tighten core and glutes, ensure back is flat and stable; prepare for the pulling motion.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Row — exhale, drive elbows upward and backward (not just lifting with arms), pulling weight toward lower chest / upper abdomen / hip (depending on variation), maintaining control, back stable, bar or dumbbell close to body.\n* 4 s–5 s: Contraction hold — at top of movement (when weight is closest to body), hold for ~0.2–0.5 s, squeeze back muscles (lats, middle-/upper-back, rear delts), keep posture steady.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / Return — inhale, slowly lower the weight back to starting position, arms extended, under control; avoid dropping or letting momentum do work.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / Ready for next rep — posture stable, weight down or hanging, core engaged, ready for next repetition or clip end.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Back muscles — especially Latissimus dorsi (lats), Rhomboids, Trapezius (middle/upper), rear shoulders (posterior deltoids).\n* Secondary / Support: Arms (biceps, forearms) for grip and elbow flexion; lower back & spinal erectors for stabilizing torso; core (abs, obliques) and glutes/hamstrings for hip-hinge posture.\nBenefits / Purpose\n* Builds a strong, thick back — improves posture, scapular control and helps combat effects of prolonged sitting or poor posture.\n* Balanced development — pulling/rowing movements balance pushing exercises (bench-press, push-ups), supporting upper-body muscular harmony and reducing shoulder/upper-back imbalances.\n* Functional strength — improves stabilization, trunk strength, and functional pulling/pulling-up type motions; beneficial for daily tasks and athletic activities.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Maintain a neutral spine — avoid rounding or over-arching the back. Hinge from hips and keep torso stable.\n* Lead with the elbow, not the hand — drive the elbow back and up to maximize lat and upper-back engagement, and avoid over-using biceps.\n* Control the tempo — both lifting and lowering should be steady and controlled; avoid jerking or swinging the weight to prevent lower-back strain and ensure muscle activation.\n* Use appropriate weight/load — especially if new; start light to master movement and posture before increasing weight.",
