      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip, ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Typical gym lighting — cable-machine metallic parts, neutral/dark gym floor, subject in standard gym attire; soft key-light + subtle ambient fill to highlight back, arms, and cable handle\n* Sound: Soft ambient (cable/weight stack movement, bench/floor contact, controlled breath), no voice-over (or optional subtle breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym (or home-gym with a cable pulley/row machine). Bench and footplate placed correctly, space cleared around so viewer sees posture and movement clearly.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing full upper body, seat, footplate, cable and handle, so both back posture and arm motion are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic (or normal) build, wearing gym clothes (tank or fitted tee + shorts/leggings), seated with feet on footrests, ready to row.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits on seat, feet firmly on foot-platform/plate, knees slightly bent, back straight, chest up, shoulders relaxed; arms extended forward holding handle (neutral or overhand/underhand grip), cable taut.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — engage core, glutes; retract scapula (pull shoulder blades back and down) to set stable upper-back posture.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Concentric phase — exhale, drive elbows straight back toward torso (not flaring out), pulling handle toward lower ribs / upper abdomen; consciously lead with elbows to maximize back muscle engagement (lats, rhomboids, traps).\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak contraction / Hold — at full pull when handle is close to body, pause ~0.2-0.5 s; squeeze back muscles, shoulder blades pinched, chest up — highlight muscle engagement and posture.\n* 5 s–7 s: Eccentric / Return phase — inhale, slowly extend arms forward under control, allowing shoulder blades to protract just enough, not collapsing posture; maintain back straight and tension.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / Ready — arms extended, cable under tension or near start, posture stable, slight pause before next rep or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats), Rhomboids (upper-back between shoulder-blades), Trapezius (middle/upper back)\n* Secondary / Supporting: Biceps (for elbow flexion), forearms (grip), rear-delts (posterior shoulders), and stabilizers — core, lower back, glutes (for posture & stability)\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Effective for building back thickness and width — develops middle-upper back (rhomboids, traps) and lats, contributing to stronger posture and back definition.\n* Safer / lower-back friendly compared to many bent-over rows — because you are seated and torso remains stable, reducing spinal load while still working the back.\n* Great for balanced upper-body development — works pulling muscles (back, biceps) to balance pushing exercises (bench, push-ups), helping posture, shoulder health, and functional strength.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Keep back straight and chest up — avoid rounding or hunching shoulders especially when arms are extended.\n* Lead with elbows, not hands — pulling with elbows ensures back muscles do the work rather than over-relying on arms/biceps\n* Controlled motion — both during pull and return; don’t use momentum or jerk the handle. Smooth, controlled reps maximize muscle engagement and limit risk.\n* Full range of motion — extend arms fully on eccentric, pull fully without cutting short; ensures proper stretch and contraction of back muscles.\n* Appropriate resistance — start with manageable weight to master form, then gradually increase; heavy loads often lead to form breakdown or excessive torso movement.",
