      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — about 8 seconds total\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Typical gym lighting — metallic bar on Smith machine, neutral/dark gym floor, subject in standard gym wear; soft directional light with ambient fill to highlight back muscles, bar path, posture\n* Sound: Ambient gym sounds (bar/plate shift, slight rail movement, breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breathing cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym with a Smith machine (vertical or slightly angled rail), bar loaded appropriately, area cleared around for safe hip-hinge and row motion\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at torso level) — capturing full upper-body, bar, hips, back alignment, and the pulling motion path from start to finish\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted gym clothing (tank/t-shirt + shorts/training pants), standing with feet shoulder-width, ready in hip-hinge row position\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands close to the bar, feet ~shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent; torso hinged forward (~15–30° from vertical, depending on machine and bar path), back straight/neutral, core & glutes engaged; hands grip bar about shoulder-width (or moderately wider) with overhand grip, arms extended downward.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace & unhook — take breath, stabilize posture, ensure bar is unlocked safely, maintain tight core and stable spine before pull begins.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Row up — exhale, drive elbows back and upward (close to body), pull bar toward lower ribs or upper abdomen (depending on torso angle and grip), shoulder blades retract and squeeze; keep back flat, torso stable, bar path straight.\n* 4 s–5 s: Contraction / Hold — at peak row, hold for ~0.2–0.5 s: chest up, shoulder blades pinched, back muscles (lats, traps, rhomboids) activated, minimal torso sway.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / Return — inhale, slowly extend arms, control bar descent back to start position, maintain posture (spine neutral, knees slightly bent), avoid letting the bar drop or using momentum.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / Ready — bar hanging at full arm extension, torso stable, slight pause (~0.3–0.5 s) before next rep or end clip\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Back — especially Latissimus dorsi (lats), Rhomboids, middle & lower Trapezius (mid-back).\n* Secondary / Supporting: Posterior deltoids (rear shoulders), biceps & forearms (for grip/elbow flexion), spinal erectors & lower-back muscles (to keep spine stable), core and glutes (for hip-hinge posture)\nBenefits & Why Use Smith-Machine Row\n* More stable and controlled than free-weight rows: the guided bar path reduces balance demands, making it easier to focus on back muscle activation safely — beneficial for beginners or those wary of lower-back strain.\n* Good for back development and hypertrophy: since you can row with controlled motion and safety, it’s well-suited for building upper-back thickness, scapular control, and lat strength.\n* Acts as a teaching tool / transition exercise: useful if you’re learning hip-hinge posture and rowing mechanics before moving to free-weight bent-over rows or more advanced lifts.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral — avoid rounding or excessive arching; hinge at hips, knees slightly bent, core engaged.\n* Lead with elbows — focus on pulling the bar with elbows back (not lifting with arms), to maximize back activation rather than biceps or arms.\n* Controlled tempo — both the pulling and lowering phases should be slow and deliberate; avoid jerking or using momentum to lift.\n* Adjust bar height and stance based on your machine — because machine rails restrict path, set bar at a comfortable height relative to your torso/hip hinge and ensure safety catches are appropriately positioned.\n* Use moderate weight, especially as beginner — heavier loads may tempt you into form breakdown; once stable, slowly progress weight while keeping strict form.",
