      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic/instructional strength clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Realistic gym or home-gym lighting (neutral/dark floor or mat, dumbbells metallic, skin tones warm/neutral); soft directional key-light + ambient fill to highlight shoulders, traps, and dumbbells during the movement\n* Sound: Soft ambient (e.g. subtle metal clink, floor/mat contact, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space — gym hall or home-gym, stable ground, minimal background clutter, enough room for standing and dumbbell holding.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — captures full upper body from head to mid-thigh, showing shoulder/trap movement, dumbbells by sides, and posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), standing upright, dumbbells held at sides, ready for shrug.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands tall with feet about shoulder-width apart (or slightly narrower), knees soft but stable; dumbbells held at sides, arms straight (or minimal bend), palms facing thighs/neutral grip; posture erect, chest up, core & glutes engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — ensure shoulders relaxed downward, neck aligned with spine (head neutral, gaze forward), prepare for upward motion; engage core to stabilize torso.\n* 2 s–4 s: Shrug up — exhale, lift (elevate) shoulders straight up toward your ears (as if trying to “touch your shoulders to ears”), raising dumbbells while keeping arms straight, avoiding elbow bend or arm swing.\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak / hold contraction — at highest point, hold the shoulder-elevated position ~0.2–0.5 seconds; feel maximal contraction in upper traps; keep posture stable, no body sway or momentum.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / return — inhale, slowly lower shoulders back to start position under control; allow traps to stretch slightly, dumbbells return to sides; avoid dropping or jerking.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / hold — stand tall again, posture stable, dumbbells hanging by sides, ready for next rep or clip fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Trapezius (upper-traps) — main muscle responsible for elevating the shoulder blades, hence the focus of shrugs.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Rhomboids and mid/upper-back stabilizers (for scapular control), forearms (for grip — holding dumbbells), and stabilizer muscles including core (abs/obliques), lower-back, glutes — to maintain posture and control.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Upper-back / trap hypertrophy — helps build size and strength in the traps, which contributes to shoulder/neck strength, posture, and upper-body aesthetics.\n* Simplicity & accessibility — needs only a pair of dumbbells; no complex setup; suitable for gym or home.\n* Grip and forearm strength — because you hold heavy dumbbells, shrugs also challenge grip strength, which helps in other lifts (deadlifts, rows, etc.).\n* Posture & neck/shoulder health — strengthening traps supports shoulder-scapular stability, can improve shoulder/neck posture and reduce risk of imbalance or injury over time.\nForm & Safety Tips / Common Mistakes to Avoid\n* Keep arms straight (or minimal arm bend) — avoid bending elbows to “help” lift; shrug motion should come strictly from shoulders/traps.\n* Move straight up and down — no shoulder-rolling motion, no swinging or using momentum, no torso lean or hip thrust to generate lift; pure vertical shrug ensures trap isolation.\n* Maintain neutral spine and stable posture — head neutral, chest up, core engaged; avoid rounding or extending spine, and don’t let posture degrade under load.\n* Use controlled tempo — lift deliberately, hold at top briefly, lower slowly; this maximizes muscle tension and reduces joint/stress risk.\n* Choose appropriate weight — use a weight that allows you full range of motion with control for 8–12+ reps; avoid going too heavy if it forces you to cheat the motion or lose form.",
