      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional body-weight + resistance-band clip — ~ 6–8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Soft, neutral lighting (daylight or gym-style), minimal background to avoid distractions, warm/neutral skin tones, with emphasis on upper-body and band movement\n* Sound: Soft ambient — minimal breathing sound, gentle band-stretch noise (if audible), no voice-over (or optional soft breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Simple open space (home floor, gym area), with enough room for arms to move sideways — no bulky equipment around.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly front/side) capturing from waist up to head — so arms, shoulders, band, posture are clearly visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing fitted but simple workout clothes (t-shirt or tank + shorts/leggings), standing upright, facing camera or slight angle, holding a resistance band in front of chest.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s roughly)\n* 0–1s: Setup — subject stands with feet about hip/shoulder-width apart, knees slightly soft; hold a resistance band with both hands at chest height, palms down (or neutral), arms extended straight (small bend allowed), band slack minimal but not overly stretched; posture upright, shoulders relaxed, core braced.\n* 1–2s: Pre-tension / Brace — engage core, draw shoulders slightly back and down (scapulae slightly retracted), set posture, prepare to pull.\n* 2–4s: Pull Apart — exhale; with arms straight (or slight soft bend), move hands horizontally out to the sides, stretching the band, until arms are roughly out to sides — band tension noticeable. Focus on pulling through your shoulder blades (scapular retraction), not just arms.\n* 4–5s: Peak Contraction / Hold — at full stretch, hold for ~0.2–0.5 s, squeezing upper-back and shoulder-blade muscles (rear delts, rhomboids, traps), chest open, shoulders down (not shrugged), band fully stretched.\n* 5–7s: Return / Controlled Release — inhale; slowly bring hands back together in front of chest, controlling the band (don’t let it snap), arms return to starting position, maintain posture and core engagement.\n* 7–8s: Reset / Ready for next rep — hold start position briefly (~0.2–0.3 s), ensure posture is correct (no rounding/hunching), then either fade out or repeat.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Rear deltoids (posterior shoulder) — main active muscles during the outward pull.\n* Upper-back (scapular stabilizers): middle and lower portion of Trapezius, Rhomboids — to retract and stabilize shoulder blades.\n* Rotator-cuff muscles and scapular-stabilizers (supporting joint health and shoulder stability) — especially useful if done with palms-up / external-rotation grip variation.\nBenefits & Why Use Band Pull-Apart\n* Improves upper-back strength & posture — counters forward-shoulder posture common from desk work or frequent pressing/exercises.\n* Enhances shoulder stability & scapular control — good for rotator-cuff health, joint integrity, and safer execution of pressing or overhead lifts.\n* Simple, equipment-light and highly accessible — only a resistance band required; can be done anywhere (home, gym, office).\n* Great as warm-up, mobility / posture work, or accessory movement to complement heavier lifts (bench, overhead press, rows).\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep arms straight (or very slight bend) — don't bend elbows; the movement should come from shoulder blades and upper-back, not elbow flexing.\n* Avoid shrugging shoulders toward ears — keep shoulder blades down and back, focus on scapular retraction not elevation.\n* Use light to moderate band resistance — resistance should allow full control and range, not force you into jerky motion or “cheat” with momentum.\n* Perform controlled tempo — smooth, deliberate pull and return; avoid letting band snap back.\n* You can vary hand-position or grip (palms down, neutral, palms up) to slightly shift activation (e.g. more rotator-cuff / external-rotation emphasis).",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Rear deltoids (posterior shoulder) — main active muscles during the outward pull.\n* Upper-back (scapular stabilizers): middle and lower portion of Trapezius, Rhomboids — to retract and stabilize shoulder blades.\n* Rotator-cuff muscles and scapular-stabilizers (supporting joint health and shoulder stability) — especially useful if done with palms-up / external-rotation grip variation.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Band Pull-Apart\n* Improves upper-back strength & posture — counters forward-shoulder posture common from desk work or frequent pressing/exercises.\n* Enhances shoulder stability & scapular control — good for rotator-cuff health, joint integrity, and safer execution of pressing or overhead lifts.\n* Simple, equipment-light and highly accessible — only a resistance band required; can be done anywhere (home, gym, office).\n* Great as warm-up, mobility / posture work, or accessory movement to complement heavier lifts (bench, overhead press, rows).",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep arms straight (or very slight bend) — don't bend elbows; the movement should come from shoulder blades and upper-back, not elbow flexing.\n* Avoid shrugging shoulders toward ears — keep shoulder blades down and back, focus on scapular retraction not elevation.\n* Use light to moderate band resistance — resistance should allow full control and range, not force you into jerky motion or “cheat” with momentum.\n* Perform controlled tempo — smooth, deliberate pull and return; avoid letting band snap back.\n* You can vary hand-position or grip (palms down, neutral, palms up) to slightly shift activation (e.g. more rotator-cuff / external-rotation emphasis)."
