      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting (machine steel, neutral background, subject in gym clothes), soft key light + ambient fill to highlight back, bar, and motion path.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (cable/weight stack clink, subtle breath, seat creak), no voice-over (or optional quiet inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable lat-pulldown machine in gym (or home-gym with proper pulley). Seat adjusted; thigh-pad secured to prevent rising. Clean background, minimal distractions.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing from head down to hips/upper legs, showing full torso, cable, bar, and movement path.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing gym attire (tank or tee + shorts/training pants), seated upright, feet flat, thighs secured, ready to grip bar overhead.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — adjust the seat and thigh-pad; subject sits with thighs under pad, feet flat. Reach up and grasp the lat-pulldown bar with an overhand (pronated) grip, hands placed wide (wider than shoulder-width). Arms fully extended overhead, lats and shoulders relaxed; torso upright, chest slightly out.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — engage core, slightly lean back (~20–30°) to match line of pull, keep spine neutral, shoulders down & back, chest up.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Concentric phase — exhale, drive elbows down and back while pulling the bar toward the upper chest / clavicle area (not behind the neck) — focus on pulling with lats, not forearms. Retract and depress shoulder blades as you pull.\n* 4 s–5 s: Contraction hold — at full pull (bar near upper chest), pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s), squeeze lats / upper-back, keep chest up, shoulder blades pinched.\n* 5 s–7 s: Return / Eccentric phase — inhale, allow the bar to rise slowly, arms extending overhead under control, shoulder blades returning, maintaining posture and core stability.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / Ready — arms extended, bar at top, posture upright, ready for next rep or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — main target for width and “v-back” development.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Upper-back muscles (rhomboids, trapezius), rear deltoids, teres major/minor, biceps & forearms (as synergists), plus core and stabilizers to maintain posture.\nWhy Use Wide-Grip Lat Pulldown — Benefits\n* Emphasizes lat width and upper-back breadth, helping build the “V-shape” back and better posture.\n* Exercises vertical-pull strength, which translates to better performance in bodyweight pulls (like pull-ups) and improves shoulder stability.\n* Offers a controlled, adjustable alternative if pull-ups are difficult — good for strengthening lats without having to lift full bodyweight.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Grip with hands wider than shoulder width, but avoid going excessively wide — extremely wide grip can stress shoulder joints.\n* Keep spine neutral and chest up; avoid excessive leaning or arching of back. Maintain a slight lean (~20–30°) rather than full vertical or heavy swing.\n* Pull with elbows down/back, not by just bending arms — focus on engaging lats rather than biceps/forearms.\n* Control both downward pull and upward release — avoid jerking or using momentum. Use a weight you can move with control.\n* Stop bar at upper-chest / clavicle height — do not pull behind the neck (unsafe for shoulders) and avoid excessive torso lean or swing.",
