      "category": "back",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip, ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral-toned gym or home-gym; warm/neutral skin tones; subtle, soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight movement, posture, and kettlebell path\n* Sound: Soft ambient (floor sounds, kettlebell movement, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optionally soft breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space (gym floor or home-gym) with stable ground — ensure enough clearance in front and behind the subject.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or eye-level) — capturing full body from head to feet, kettlebell, and motion path (back-swing → forward swing).\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), standing with feet shoulder-width, ready to perform swing.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands with feet slightly wider than shoulder-width, toes maybe slightly outward; kettlebell placed on floor just ahead of feet (or lightly lifted) with both hands gripping handle, arms straight, torso upright but relaxed.\n* 1 s–2 s: Hinge & prepare — push hips back, bend knees slightly, hinge forward at hips (not squat), keep back flat/neutral, core braced, shoulders down & back — prepare to “load” the swing.\n* 2 s–3 s: Back-swing / Set up the swing — send the kettlebell back between the legs, keeping arms straight (or slight bend), letting the bell swing downward and behind you.\n* 3 s–5 s: Hip drive & swing up — vigorously drive hips forward (hip extension), squeeze glutes and hamstrings, thrusting hips to send kettlebell forward and upward; kettlebell rises to about chest- or shoulder-height (or slightly higher depending on style). Arms act as guides, not lifters.\n* 5 s–5.5 s: Peak / brief hold — at the top of swing, body upright, core tight, glutes/hamstrings engaged, shoulders stable; kettlebell in forward arc.\n* 5.5 s–7 s: Return / pendulum-drive back — allow kettlebell to swing back downward between legs (hip hinge again), controlling the motion, spine neutral, core braced.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / ready — at bottom, bell between legs or just ahead, body stable, ready for next rep or fade out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Swing Works)\n* Posterior chain: Glutes, hamstrings — main drivers during hip extension and swing.\n* Lower back / spinal stabilizers (erector spinae): Help maintain neutral spine and control during hinge and swing.\n* Core / Abdominals: Brace during swing to stabilize torso, prevent over-extension, and transfer force from hips to upper body.\n* Secondary / Supporting muscles: Quadriceps (to stabilize knees and during slight knee bend), lats/upper-back & shoulders (to guide kettlebell path, stabilize shoulders), forearms & grip muscles (holding kettlebell handle).\nBenefits & Why Use Kettlebell Swing\n* Combines strength + power + cardio — swings recruit large muscle groups explosively, improving power (hip drive), endurance, and cardiovascular capacity.\n* Excellent for posterior-chain development — builds glute/hamstring/ lower-back strength, improves posture and functional strength for daily activities (lifting, bending).\n* Enhances core stability, hip mobility, grip strength — due to dynamic movement, resisting swing, and controlling bell path.\n* Time-efficient, minimal equipment — requires only one kettlebell; effective for full-body workout in limited time.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Cues\n* Use a hip hinge, not squat — push hips back to load hamstrings/glutes; avoid deep knee bend or squatting motion.\n* Keep back neutral/flat — avoid rounding or over-arching; spine stays aligned through the motion.\n* Power comes from hip drive, not arms — arms simply guide the kettlebell; don’t “lift” the bell with shoulders or arms.\n* Controlled rhythm — avoid jerking, swinging uncontrollably, or letting the kettlebell drag you forward; let momentum be generated from hip thrust, and control descent.\n* Ensure core tightness & neutral spine — brace abs/glutes, keep chest up and shoulders down/back.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Swing Works)\n* Posterior chain: Glutes, hamstrings — main drivers during hip extension and swing.\n* Lower back / spinal stabilizers (erector spinae): Help maintain neutral spine and control during hinge and swing.\n* Core / Abdominals: Brace during swing to stabilize torso, prevent over-extension, and transfer force from hips to upper body.\n* Secondary / Supporting muscles: Quadriceps (to stabilize knees and during slight knee bend), lats/upper-back & shoulders (to guide kettlebell path, stabilize shoulders), forearms & grip muscles (holding kettlebell handle).",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Kettlebell Swing\n* Combines strength + power + cardio — swings recruit large muscle groups explosively, improving power (hip drive), endurance, and cardiovascular capacity.\n* Excellent for posterior-chain development — builds glute/hamstring/ lower-back strength, improves posture and functional strength for daily activities (lifting, bending).\n* Enhances core stability, hip mobility, grip strength — due to dynamic movement, resisting swing, and controlling bell path.\n* Time-efficient, minimal equipment — requires only one kettlebell; effective for full-body workout in limited time.",
      "safety": "/ Key Technique Cues\n* Use a hip hinge, not squat — push hips back to load hamstrings/glutes; avoid deep knee bend or squatting motion.\n* Keep back neutral/flat — avoid rounding or over-arching; spine stays aligned through the motion.\n* Power comes from hip drive, not arms — arms simply guide the kettlebell; don’t “lift” the bell with shoulders or arms.\n* Controlled rhythm — avoid jerking, swinging uncontrollably, or letting the kettlebell drag you forward; let momentum be generated from hip thrust, and control descent.\n* Ensure core tightness & neutral spine — brace abs/glutes, keep chest up and shoulders down/back."
