      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength & power clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Real-gym or home-gym style lighting: neutral/dark floor, metal implements (barbell / dumbbells / kettlebell), soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight motion, muscle/tension.\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (barbell or weight stack clinks, subtle foot shift/ground contact, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym floor (for barbell), or open floor space (with dumbbells or kettlebell) — stable ground, space to move vertically; background minimal or softly blurred to focus on lifter + weight.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) to capture the full body from feet to head, including bar/bell path, hip and knee movement, and upper-body motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted gym attire (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), ready in start stance (barbell/dumbbell/kettlebell held) to perform the High Pull.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject stands with feet approximately hip- to shoulder-width apart. Grip the barbell (or hold dumbbells/kettlebell) with overhand grip; weight close to shins (for barbell) or hanging by sides (for dumbbells). Hips pushed back slightly, knees slightly bent, back neutral, chest up, shoulders relaxed/back.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace & hinge/prepare — engage core & glutes, keep spine neutral, set lats tight; prepare to drive upward.\n* 2 s–4 s: Explosive upward drive — simultaneously extend hips, knees, and ankles (triple extension), shrug shoulders and pull elbows upward & outward, lifting the bar/bell upward while keeping it close to the body; heels may rise slightly (for added drive).\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak / highest pull — bar/bell reaches around upper chest / sternum height (or slightly higher depending on variation), elbows high, shoulder blades retracted (scapular squeeze), upper-back and traps fully engaged. Brief hold (≈ 0.2–0.5 s) at top to show full contraction and power.\n* 5 s–7 s: Controlled descent / return — lower weight under control: extend hips/legs slightly to let bar/bell descend, keep back neutral, allow arms to extend fully before next rep. Resist swinging—maintain control.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / ready stance — weight back to starting position, posture stabilized, breathing reset; ready for next repetition or fade out.\nMuscles / Focus (What High Pull Works)\n* Primary: Upper back and shoulder complex — especially traps (upper & mid), deltoids (rear and lateral), rhomboids.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Posterior chain: glutes, hamstrings, hip extensors, spinal erectors (lower back) — involved via the hip-drive; core and stabilizers engaged to maintain posture; legs (quads, calves) help with power drive; forearms & grip muscles during hold and pull.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Builds explosive full-body power and rate of force production (useful for athletic performance, explosive lifts, functional strength).\n* Enhances upper-back, shoulder, and trap development — helps build a powerful upper-body and improved posture.\n* Strengthens posterior-chain muscles and hip/leg drive — beneficial for overall strength, stability, and translating power from ground through body.\n* A more explosive, dynamic alternative or complement to traditional rows/presses — can help bridge to olympic lifts or athletic movements if needed.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Emphasize hip + knee drive rather than upper-body pull — the power should originate from legs and hips, not arms alone. Avoid over-pulling with arms or using too much upper-body “lift.”\n* Keep the bar/bell close to body — minimize horizontal distance from body to reduce leverage on spine/back and maintain control.\n* Neutral spine posture is essential — avoid rounding or over-arching. Hips and knees must be aligned and movement controlled.\n* Use explosive upward motion + controlled descent — fast and powerful lift phase, slow and stable lowering phase to reduce injury risk and maximize muscle stress.\n* Choose appropriate weight — start moderately to master form, speed, and control. Heavy loads with poor technique increase risk of strain or injury.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What High Pull Works)\n* Primary: Upper back and shoulder complex — especially traps (upper & mid), deltoids (rear and lateral), rhomboids.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Posterior chain: glutes, hamstrings, hip extensors, spinal erectors (lower back) — involved via the hip-drive; core and stabilizers engaged to maintain posture; legs (quads, calves) help with power drive; forearms & grip muscles during hold and pull.",
      "benefits": "& Purpose\n* Builds explosive full-body power and rate of force production (useful for athletic performance, explosive lifts, functional strength).\n* Enhances upper-back, shoulder, and trap development — helps build a powerful upper-body and improved posture.\n* Strengthens posterior-chain muscles and hip/leg drive — beneficial for overall strength, stability, and translating power from ground through body.\n* A more explosive, dynamic alternative or complement to traditional rows/presses — can help bridge to olympic lifts or athletic movements if needed.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Emphasize hip + knee drive rather than upper-body pull — the power should originate from legs and hips, not arms alone. Avoid over-pulling with arms or using too much upper-body “lift.”\n* Keep the bar/bell close to body — minimize horizontal distance from body to reduce leverage on spine/back and maintain control.\n* Neutral spine posture is essential — avoid rounding or over-arching. Hips and knees must be aligned and movement controlled.\n* Use explosive upward motion + controlled descent — fast and powerful lift phase, slow and stable lowering phase to reduce injury risk and maximize muscle stress.\n* Choose appropriate weight — start moderately to master form, speed, and control. Heavy loads with poor technique increase risk of strain or injury."
