      "id": "back_single_arm_cable_row_male",
      "name": "Single arm cable row",
      "gender": "male",
      "category": "back",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym with clean background; neutral/dark tones (metal cable machine, subtle lighting), soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight back, arm, cable and handle\n* Sound: Ambient gym sounds (cable stack, subtle seat/footplate noise, breath), no commentary (or optional soft breath-cue)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable-pulley machine (single-handle low pulley or seated row machine), clear space, foot-pad or platform set, bench or seat if applicable.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) — capturing upper body, torso, cable, handle, and torso posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing workout attire (fitted tee/tank + gym pants), seated or standing (depending on variation), holding the handle with one hand; other hand may rest on thigh/bench for support if seated.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits (or stands) with a single-handle attached to cable. If seated: feet on foot-pads, knees slightly bent, torso upright; other hand resting lightly for balance. Handle is held with neutral or overhand grip; arm extended, cable taut, shoulder relaxed.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — engage core, keep back straight, retract shoulder blades slightly (shoulders down & back), prepare for the pull.\n* 2 s–4 s: Pull / Concentric phase — exhale; pull the handle with elbow close to body, driving elbow backward toward your hip or lower rib cage. Focus on using your back muscles (lats, rhomboids) rather than arm-only.\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak / Contraction hold — when handle is fully pulled in, pause for ~0.2–0.5 s; squeeze shoulder-blade region and feel contraction across lats and upper/mid-back.\n* 5 s–7 s: Lower / Return phase — inhale; slowly extend arm forward, under control, fully stretching lats while maintaining posture; avoid letting weight snap forward.\n* 7 s–8 s: Reset / ready-position — arm extended, back up straight, core engaged; optional slight pause then repeat or end clip.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Back — especially Latissimus dorsi (lats), along with upper/mid-back muscles such as Rhomboids and Trapezius (middle/upper portion).\n* Secondary / Supporting: Rear shoulder (posterior deltoid), biceps and forearms (for elbow flexion / grip), plus core and lower-back (for stabilization), because you resist rotation and stabilize the torso while pulling one-sided.\nBenefits & Why Use Single-Arm Cable Row\n* Enables unilateral training, which helps correct left/right imbalances — each side works independently rather than dominant side compensating.\n* Improves mind-muscle connection — because only one arm works, easier to focus on contracting back muscles properly.\n* Enhances core stability & posture — unilateral load forces core and trunk stabilizers to prevent unwanted rotation or sway.\n* Provides constant tension through full range of motion — cable resistance gives steady load from start to finish, aiding hypertrophy and muscle engagement.\nCommon Mistakes & Safety / Form Tips\n* Avoid twisting or rotating torso when pulling — stabilise core and keep torso square.\n* Don’t rely on arm only — lead movement with elbow, not hand, to engage back rather than biceps.\n* Use controlled tempo — both pull and release should be smooth, avoid jerking or letting momentum do the work.\n* Start with moderate weight — ensure you can perform full range with good form; too heavy load often leads to form breakdown.",
