      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Typical gym lighting (cable machine metallic, neutral/dark gym floor or mat, minimal background distractions), soft key light + ambient fill to highlight back, shoulder, cable handle, and posture\n* Sound: Soft ambient — slight cable/weight stack click, subtle breath, minimal noise; no voice-over (optionally soft inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable-pulley machine (lat-pulldown station or high-pulley) with a single-handle attachment. Seat adjusted (or standing/kneeling setup if preferred). Machine and floor cleared of distractions.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly side-front) — frames from head to hips/upper legs, capturing torso position, shoulder, arm path, cable handle, and slight body stabilization.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing workout clothes (tank or t-shirt + shorts/training pants), seated or kneeling or standing (depending on setup), holding the single handle with one hand, ready to pull.\nAction / Beats (0s–8s)\n* 0 s–1 s — Setup: Subject attaches one-hand handle to the top pulley, sits (or kneels/stands) with feet stable (knees slightly bent if seated), back straight, core engaged. Arm extended overhead/forward holding handle; other hand rests (on seat/thigh) or is free for balance. Shoulders relaxed.\n* 1 s–2 s — Brace & engage: Engage core and glutes, retract and depress shoulder blade on working side (shoulder down & back), chest up, spine neutral — prepare for pull.\n* 2 s–4 s — Pull / concentric phase: Exhale; pull the handle downward toward your side/upper rib or hip, keeping elbow close to body, leading the motion with elbow rather than hand, ensuring full lat engagement. Allow a slight controlled lean/side bend if cable path requires.\n* 4 s–5 s — Contraction hold: At the bottom of the pull (handle near side/hip), pause ~0.2–0.5 s, squeeze the back muscles (lats, rhomboids), keep shoulder-blade retracted, torso stable.\n* 5 s–7 s — Eccentric / Return: Inhale; slowly extend arm back to start under control, allowing lats to stretch, ensuring smooth, non-jerky motion. Avoid letting torso twist or sway; maintain core engagement and posture.\n* 7 s–8 s — Reset / ready: Arm extended, back upright, core stable, ready for next rep or for fade-out in video.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Main: Latissimus dorsi (lats) — primary driver of the downward/adduction motion of the arm.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Rhomboids, mid & lower Trapezius (upper-back), rear deltoid (rear shoulder), also forearms/biceps for grip and elbow flexion, and core & obliques for stabilization due to unilateral load.\nBenefits & Why Use One-Arm Lat Pulldown\n* Unilateral training: Helps identify and correct left-right strength or muscular imbalances; ensures both sides of the back are worked equally.\n* Improved mind-muscle connection & lat isolation: Because only one arm works at a time, easier to focus on lat activation and form, reducing compensations from dominant side.\n* Increased range of motion and flexibility: The unilateral pull allows for a more natural path and possibly greater stretch/contraction than bilat pulldown bar.\n* Core activation & stability challenge: The need to stabilize torso and resist rotation increases core and trunk engagement — beneficial for posture and functional strength.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep torso stable and spine neutral — avoid excessive twisting, leaning, or momentum; control both concentric and eccentric parts of the rep.\n* Lead with the elbow (not hand) — focus on pulling through your back muscles, not arm/forearm pull to prevent over-recruitment of biceps and to ensure lat engagement.\n* Use a manageable weight — since you're using one arm, choose lighter load than bilateral pulldown; allows full range of motion without compromising form.\n* Maintain smooth, controlled tempo — avoid jerky motions or letting weight drop quickly; think “pull-pause-control release.”",
