      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength-clip — about 8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym (or home-gym) standard lighting: bench visible, dumbbells metallic, neutral background to keep focus on subject; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight back, arms, bench and dumbbells\n* Sound: Soft ambient (dumbbell weight shift, bench contact, subtle breathing), no voice-over — optionally soft breath-in / breath-out cues\nScene Setup\n* Location: Adjustable incline bench (set ~30–45°), with enough space behind for dumbbells and space to move. Clear background.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle, slightly low/side — capturing body from head to mid-thigh, bench, dumbbells, and clear row-motion path.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing gym attire (tank/tee + shorts/gym pants), lying prone (face-down) on bench at incline, chest on pad, feet on floor for stability, holding dumbbells in both hands.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s (Setup): Subject lies chest-down on incline bench, chest firmly in contact with pad; feet planted. Dumbbells held in both hands, arms extended down naturally toward floor (palms facing each other / neutral grip). Core & glutes engaged.\n* 1–2 s (Brace): Slightly retract shoulder blades (shoulders back & down), keep torso stable against pad, ensure body is tight, ready to row.\n* 2–4 s (Pull / Concentric): Exhale; pull both dumbbells upward in an arc, driving elbows back toward torso/hip-line, squeezing shoulder blades together as dumbbells rise. Ensure forearms guide but elbow-driven motion for better back activation.\n* 4–5 s (Contraction / Hold): At top of row, hold briefly (~0.2–0.5 s); back/upper-back muscles (lats, middle/upper-back, rear delts) fully contracted; chest remains in contact with bench.\n* 5–7 s (Lower / Eccentric): Inhale; slowly lower dumbbells back to starting position with control, arms long again, allowing full stretch of back muscles; maintain contact with bench and keep torso stable.\n* 7–8 s (Reset / End): Arms extended, dumbbells hanging, body still prone on bench; minimal motion — ready for next rep or clip end.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Back — particularly the latissimus dorsi (lats), rhomboids, middle & lower traps, rear deltoids (upper-back muscles).\n* Secondary / Supporting: Biceps & forearms (for grip and elbow flexion), upper/mid-back stabilizers, core & glutes for torso stability (even though bench supports body), also some lower-back stability but less than free bent-over row because bench supports torso.\nBenefits & Why Use Incline Dumbbell Row\n* Provides better back isolation: because chest is supported on bench, there’s minimal momentum/swing — this places more emphasis on upper- and mid-back muscles rather than using legs/hips or lower-back stabilization.\n* Reduces stress on lower back/legs — unlike bent-over rows or free variations, this variation is gentler on lower back and safer if one has lower-back or hip issues.\n* Allows strict form and full range of motion — bench support keeps torso stable so you can focus on pulling, squeezing and muscle contraction, maximizing lat and upper-back engagement.\n* Good for balanced back development — hits lats, middle/back thickness, rear-delts; complements vertical (pull-ups/pulldowns) and other row variations to build full back strength & posture.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep chest in contact with bench throughout — don’t lift or arch away; this ensures back muscles do the work and avoids cheating via momentum.\n* Use controlled motion — lift (pull) and lower (release) slowly; avoid jerking or swinging weights.\n* Lead the movement with elbows, not hands — focus on pulling elbows back to engage lats / upper-back; avoid curling with arms/biceps.\n* Choose appropriate/ manageable weight — because bench supports torso, you might be tempted to use heavy dumbbells; pick a weight that allows clean full-range reps without straining or sacrificing form.",
